# Xcode
#
# gitignore contributors: remember to update Global/Xcode.gitignore, Objective-C.gitignore & Swift.gitignore

## User settings
# Ignored because: contains per-developer IDE preferences (breakpoints, UI layout, colour themes).
# If committed: every developer would constantly overwrite each other's personal Xcode settings,
# causing noisy diffs and merge conflicts on every pull.
xcuserdata/

## Compatibility with Xcode 8 and earlier (ignoring not required starting Xcode 9)
# Ignored because: legacy source control blueprint files auto-generated by old Xcode versions.
# If committed: pollutes the repo with obsolete metadata that modern Xcode neither reads nor needs.
*.xcscmblueprint
*.xccheckout

## Compatibility with Xcode 3 and earlier (ignoring not required starting Xcode 4)
# Ignored because: local build output directory created by Xcode during compilation.
# If committed: bloats the repo with compiled binaries and intermediates that are always
# reproducible from source, potentially adding gigabytes of binary noise.
build/

# Ignored because: Xcode's private scratch space for all intermediate build products,
# indexes, and code coverage data, scoped per-developer by UUID.
# If committed: causes constant merge conflicts and repo bloat; the path contains
# a UUID unique to each machine, making it meaningless to other developers.
DerivedData/

# Ignored because: a backup copy Xcode creates when renaming/moving files.
# If committed: leaves confusing duplicate source files in the repo with no purpose.
*.moved-aside

# Ignored because: legacy per-user Xcode 3 project settings file storing window state and breakpoints.
# If committed: every developer would fight over this file on every commit; !default.pbxuser
# is kept to preserve the shared default baseline that Xcode ships with.
*.pbxuser
!default.pbxuser

# Ignored because: legacy Xcode 3 window mode preference files storing layout state per developer.
# If committed: causes pointless merge conflicts every time someone rearranges their Xcode panels.
*.mode1v3
!default.mode1v3
*.mode2v3
!default.mode2v3

# Ignored because: legacy Xcode 3 perspective files storing per-developer UI layout.
# If committed: same as mode files — constant low-value merge conflicts with zero shared benefit.
*.perspectivev3
!default.perspectivev3

## Obj-C/Swift specific
# Ignored because: header map files are a build-time index Xcode generates to speed up
# header lookups during compilation. They are machine-specific and always regenerated.
# If committed: breaks builds on other machines since the paths embedded inside are absolute
# and point to the original developer's filesystem.
*.hmap

## App packaging
# Ignored because: compiled and signed app archive ready for distribution.
# If committed: massive binary that changes on every build, would bloat the repo rapidly
# and is always reproducible via a clean build + archive.
*.ipa

# Ignored because: compressed debug symbol files used to symbolicate crash reports.
# If committed: large binary files that grow the repo significantly; they should be
# uploaded to a crash reporting service (Crashlytics, Sentry, etc.) instead.
*.dSYM.zip
*.dSYM

## Test results (Xcode 11+)
# Ignored because: binary test result bundles generated after every test run, containing
# logs, screenshots, and performance metrics specific to one run on one machine.
# If committed: rapidly bloats the repo with large binaries; CI systems archive these
# separately and they have no value in source control history.
*.xcresult

## Playgrounds
# Ignored because: legacy XML file storing the execution timeline for Xcode Playgrounds,
# auto-generated by Xcode versions prior to 10. The Timeline feature no longer exists.
# If committed: adds obsolete, auto-regenerated noise with no value for any team member.
timeline.xctimeline

# Ignored because: Xcode auto-generates this workspace inside every .playground bundle
# when you open it. It contains no authored content, only machine state.
# If committed: causes spurious diffs every time any developer opens the playground.
playground.xcworkspace

# Swift Package Manager
#
# Package.resolved behaviour:
#   - Apps:      COMMIT Package.resolved — locks dependency versions for reproducible builds
#   - Libraries: IGNORE Package.resolved — lets dependents resolve their own version graph
#
# Uncomment the next line if this repo is a Swift library:
# Package.resolved

# Ignored because: Xcode auto-generates a local workspace inside .swiftpm/ purely to open
# the package in Xcode. It contains no project configuration you would author yourself.
# If committed: causes constant noise diffs for every developer who opens the package in Xcode.
.swiftpm/xcode/package.xcworkspace/*
!.swiftpm/xcode/package.xcworkspace/xcshareddata/

# Ignored because: the Swift Package Manager's local build output folder containing
# compiled object files, module maps, and intermediates for all resolved packages.
# If committed: bloats the repo with gigabytes of machine-specific binary build products
# that are always fully reproducible with `swift build`.
.build/

# CocoaPods
#
# We recommend against adding the Pods directory to your .gitignore file.
# You should judge for yourself; the pros and cons are documented at:
# https://guides.cocoapods.org/using/using-cocoapods.html#should-i-check-the-pods-directory-into-source-control
#
# Ignored because: the Pods/ directory contains all CocoaPods dependency source code,
# which is fully reproducible by running `pod install` with the committed Podfile.lock.
# If committed: massively bloats the repo (often 100MB–1GB+) and creates enormous
# diffs on every `pod update`, drowning out real code changes.
Pods/

# Ignored because: Xcode generates this workspace to tie together your project and the
# Pods project when CocoaPods is used. It is auto-regenerated by `pod install`.
# If committed: causes merge conflicts when different developers run `pod install` at
# different times, since the workspace content is derived, not authored.
# Exception: xcshareddata/ is carved out below because it contains the SPM Package.resolved
# lock file that Xcode writes when you add remote packages via the Xcode UI. Without
# committing it, the team has no shared record of which exact dependency versions are in use.
*.xcworkspace
!*.xcworkspace/xcshareddata/
!*.xcworkspace/xcshareddata/**

# Carthage
#
# Ignored because: the Build/ folder contains pre-compiled Carthage frameworks.
# These are large binary artifacts always reproducible by running `carthage bootstrap`.
# If committed: dramatically increases repo size and checkout time with binaries
# that differ per platform and architecture slice (arm64, x86_64, etc.).
# Note: Carthage/Checkouts can optionally be committed for fully offline builds.
Carthage/Build/

# Tuist
#
# Tuist is a widely used project generation tool for Xcode projects.
# https://tuist.io

# Ignored because: the local Tuist binary installed by `tuist install` for this project.
# If committed: forces all developers to use the exact same binary path, breaking setups
# where Tuist is managed differently; the version is already pinned in .tuist-version.
.tuist-bin/

# Ignored because: Tuist's local cache and configuration state directory.
# If committed: contains machine-specific paths and cache metadata that are meaningless
# and potentially misleading to other developers.
.tuist/

# Ignored because: the Derived/ folder is where Tuist writes all generated Xcode project
# files (.xcodeproj, .xcworkspace). These are always regenerated by running `tuist generate`.
# If committed: creates enormous noisy diffs every time project structure changes, since
# the generated files are verbose XML not meant to be read or maintained by hand.
Derived/

# Ignored because: local SPM build artifacts produced when Tuist itself resolves its
# own plugin or helper dependencies. Fully reproducible and machine-specific.
# If committed: adds binary build noise completely unrelated to your app's source code.
Tuist/.build/

# XcodeGen
#
# If you generate your .xcodeproj via XcodeGen, you typically don't commit it since
# it is always reproducible by running `xcodegen generate` from project.yml.
# Uncomment the next line if that is your setup:
# *.xcodeproj

# fastlane
#
# It is recommended to not store the screenshots in the git repo.
# Instead, use fastlane to re-generate the screenshots whenever they are needed.
# For more information about the recommended setup visit:
# https://docs.fastlane.tools/best-practices/source-control/#source-control

# Ignored because: auto-generated XML report of the last fastlane run, containing
# pass/fail results and timing data specific to one CI or local execution.
# If committed: causes a noisy diff after every single lane execution with no
# historical value since it only ever reflects the most recent run.
fastlane/report.xml

# Ignored because: an HTML preview file fastlane generates when capturing screenshots.
# This is a local convenience file for reviewing captures and is always regenerated.
# If committed: adds a constantly changing file with zero value in history.
fastlane/Preview.html

# Ignored because: App Store screenshots captured by fastlane's snapshot/screengrab tool.
# These can be hundreds of MB across all device sizes and locales, and are always
# reproducible by re-running the snapshot lane.
# If committed: rapidly bloats the repo and creates enormous diffs on every screenshot update.
fastlane/screenshots/**/*.png

# Ignored because: directory containing raw test output (logs, junit XML, videos) from
# fastlane's scan/run_tests action, scoped to a single CI run.
# If committed: fills the repo with large, machine-specific test artifacts that CI systems
# already archive separately as build artifacts.
fastlane/test_output

# Code Injection
#
# Ignored because: project folder generated by InjectionForXcode / InjectionIII to enable
# hot-reload of Swift code during development. It is auto-created on first use and contains
# only local build glue with no value outside the original developer's machine.
# If committed: adds a confusing folder that breaks or does nothing on other developers'
# machines and implies a runtime dependency that most team members may not have installed.
iOSInjectionProject/
InjectionIII/

# macOS
# Ignored because: hidden metadata files macOS creates in every directory to store Finder
# view options (icon positions, background colour, sort order, etc.).
# If committed: pollutes every directory listing in the repo with OS-level noise and
# can expose local directory structure details irrelevant to the project.
.DS_Store
**/.DS_Store
